\subsection{Operational Interpretation: Entanglement Swapping Automaton}

After the Page time, $U_n$ performs entanglement swapping from memory–early-radiation to late–early radiation, mediated by $M_{n-1}$. The memory acts as a catalytic buffer establishing long-range temporal correlations while preserving local Unruh vacuum properties (see Sec.~\ref{sec:no_firewall}).

\section{The No-Firewall Lemma: Gentleness and Local Vacua}
\label{sec:no_firewall}

\begin{lemma}[No-Firewall Lemma]
\label{lem:nofirewall}
Let $\mathcal{O}_{\rm loc}$ be a local operator supported in a freely falling worldtube of size $\ell\ll R_s$. Under P3,
\begin{equation}
    \norm{\rho_{\rm loc}-\ket{0_{\rm Mink}}\!\bra{0_{\rm Mink}}}_1 \ \le\ O(1/S_{\rm BH}),
\end{equation}
and the renormalized stress-energy tensor obeys
\begin{equation}
    \Delta\!\big\langle T_{ab} u^a u^b \big\rangle_{\rm infall} \ \lesssim\ \frac{\hbar}{R_s^4}\,\frac{1}{S_{\rm BH}} \ll \kappa^4.
    \label{eq:gentleness}
\end{equation}
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}[Sketch]
Using the Keldysh description (Sec.~\ref{sec:influence}) with a smooth, causal, retarded kernel $K$, the modified Wightman function remains Hadamard~\cite{Radzikowski:1996}; Appendix \ref{app:stress_tensor} provides details. Quantum energy inequalities~\cite{Fewster:2012} then yield Eq.~\eqref{eq:gentleness}.
\end{proof}

\subsection{Resolution of the AMPS Paradox}

The HMC state is fundamentally multipartite. Post-Page, $R_n$ is purified by $(I_n M_n R_{<n})$ jointly, preserving monogamy and local smoothness.

\section{The Final State of Evaporation: Discharge of the Memory Register}
\label{sec:end_state}

As $A(u)\to O(\ell_p^2)$, $d_M\to O(1)$ (P0). The information has been unitarily released into $R_{\le n_{\rm evap}}$, leaving no high-entropy remnant. A universal, low-energy \emph{soft afterglow} may occur during final memory discharge.

\section{Microstate Origin of Entropy: Memory as Edge Modes}
\label{sec:microstates}

We identify $\mathcal{H}_{\rm mem}$ with time-like gravitational edge modes on a stretched horizon $\mathcal{N}$~\cite{'tHooft:1985, Susskind:1993, Donnelly:2016, Carlip:2017}. Quantization of the boundary charge algebra yields
\begin{equation}
    \log\dim \mathcal{H}_{\rm edge} \ =\ \frac{A}{4G\hbar} - \frac{\gamma}{2}\log\!\Big(\frac{A}{\ell_p^2}\Big) + O(1),
\end{equation}
consistent with P0.

\subsection{From Edge Mode Dynamics to P1--P4 (Qualitative)}
Unitarity (P1) follows from the underlying unitary quantum gravity. Fast-scrambling (P2) reflects gravitational chaos near horizons~\cite{Sekino:2008}. Gentleness (P3) arises since edge modes are soft, long-wavelength excitations with suppressed local energy densities. Adiabatic information transfer (P4) is enforced by unitarity as the memory capacity shrinks.

\section{Deriving the HMC Postulates and Memory Kernel from Candidate Quantum Gravity}
\label{sec:derive_qg}

We present explicit derivations from two complementary models: (i) 4D gravity with a stretched-horizon boundary and edge-mode Chern–Simons/WZW structure, and (ii) the nearly-AdS$_2$ Jackiw–Teitelboim (JT) gravity, whose boundary reparametrization (Schwarzian) mode provides a tractable microscopic realization.

\subsection{Stretched Horizon, Edge Modes, and Boundary Action}
Start from the Einstein–Hilbert action with Gibbons–Hawking–York (GHY) term and corner terms,
\begin{equation}
S_{\rm GR}=\frac{1}{16\pi G}\int_{\mathcal{M}}\! d^4x\,\sqrt{-g}\,R+\frac{1}{8\pi G}\int_{\partial\mathcal{M}}\! d^3x\,\sqrt{-h}\,K+\cdots.
\end{equation}
Introduce a time-like stretched horizon $\mathcal{N}$ at proper distance $\sim \ell_p$ from the true horizon. Gauge fixing in the bulk leaves residual diffeomorphisms on $\mathcal{N}$, which become physical edge modes with associated surface charges~\cite{Donnelly:2016}. The induced boundary action can often be recast into a Chern–Simons/WZW-like theory (depending on dimension/reduction), with a symplectic structure on the space of edge-mode fields (schematically, $\eta(u,\Omega)$) and their charges $Q[\xi]$. Quantization of this boundary phase space yields a finite-dimensional Hilbert space with $\log \dim \mathcal{H}_{\rm edge} = A/(4G\hbar) + \cdots$, establishing P0 from state counting. Local matter fields couple minimally to the boundary via
\begin{equation}
S_{\rm int}=\int_{\mathcal{N}} d^3x \sqrt{-h}\, g\, \mathcal{O}_{\rm edge}(x)\, \phi(x),
\label{eq:boundary_int}
\end{equation}
where $\mathcal{O}_{\rm edge}$ is a boundary operator built from the edge-mode fields (e.g., deformations of the embedding data or normal extrinsic curvature fluctuations). This coupling is soft and causal.

\paragraph{Information-theoretic postulates from the boundary theory.}
- P1: The combined system $(\phi, \mathrm{edge})$ evolves unitarily, with the horizon boundary providing a persistent memory line $\mathcal{H}_{\rm edge}(u)$ updated by local interactions.
- P2: Strong gravitational chaos near horizons (e.g., Lyapunov exponent $\lambda_L=2\pi T_H$) implies fast scrambling of information within the high-dimensional $\mathcal{H}_{\rm edge}$, justifying typicality of $U_n$.
- P3: The low-energy character of edge modes implies that matrix elements inducing hard excitations are suppressed by inverse powers of the entropy or area, leading to $\epsilon=O(1/S_{\rm BH})$ deviations in local detectors.
- P4: As $A(u)$ decreases, sectors of $\mathcal{H}_{\rm edge}$ decouple; unitarity mandates coherent information transfer to the only external system available: outgoing radiation.

\subsection{JT Gravity and the Schwarzian Boundary Mode: Explicit Kernel}
In a near-horizon, s-wave reduction, the dynamics are well captured by nearly-AdS$_2$ (JT) gravity coupled to matter~\cite{Almheiri:2015, Maldacena:2016SYK, MSY:2016, Jensen:2016}. The JT action
\begin{equation}
S_{\rm JT}=-\frac{\phi_0}{2}\int R - \frac{1}{2}\int \phi (R+2) + S_{\rm bdy}[\phi] + S_{\rm matter}
\end{equation}
induces a boundary reparametrization mode $f(u)$ with Schwarzian action
\begin{equation}
S_{\rm Schw}[f]=\frac{C}{2}\int du\, \{f(u),u\},\qquad C\propto \phi_r \sim S_{\rm BH},
\end{equation}
where $\{f,u\}$ is the Schwarzian derivative and $\phi_r$ the renormalized dilaton. Matter couples to $f$ through the induced boundary curve; to leading order, this coupling can be written schematically as
\begin{equation}
S_{\rm int}=\int du\, g\, \mathcal{O}_{\rm Schw}(u)\, \phi(u)\,,
\label{eq:JT_coupling}
\end{equation}
where $\mathcal{O}_{\rm Schw}$ is an operator constructed from $f$ and its derivatives that deforms the map between near-horizon and asymptotic modes. Integrating out the Schwarzian mode yields a Keldysh influence functional (compare Eq.~\eqref{eq:influence_functional}) with a causal memory kernel proportional to the retarded correlator of $\mathcal{O}_{\rm Schw}$,
\begin{equation}
\Xi^R(u-u')= i\,g^2\,\Theta(u-u') \,\langle[\mathcal{O}_{\rm Schw}(u),\mathcal{O}_{\rm Schw}(u')]\rangle.
\end{equation}
At finite temperature $T_H=1/\beta$, the frequency-domain kernel takes a universal form controlled by the Schwarzian two-point function~\cite{Maldacena:2016SYK, MSY:2016}:
\begin{equation}
\Xi^R(\omega)\ =\ \frac{g^2}{C}\,\Big[\psi\!\Big(1+\frac{i \beta \omega}{2\pi}\Big)+\psi\!\Big(1-\frac{i \beta \omega}{2\pi}\Big) - 2\psi(1)\Big] \,+\, O(C^{-2}),
\label{eq:kernel_schwarzian}
\end{equation}
where $\psi$ is the digamma function and $C\propto S_{\rm BH}$ sets the overall scale. Thus,
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Amplitude scaling}: $\Xi^R \propto g^2/C \sim O(1/S_{\rm BH})$ for fixed $g$, establishing P3 quantitatively.
\item \textbf{Timescale}: The kernel inherits thermal periodicity and decays on scales set by $\beta$ but can be extended by scrambling effects; higher-order resummations generate logarithmic enhancements leading to memory times $\tau_{\rm mem}\sim \beta \log S_{\rm BH}$ (scrambling) up to Page-scale tails depending on interactions.
\item \textbf{Causality}: Ensured by the retarded prescription and KMS relations.
\end{itemize}
Fourier transforming Eq.~\eqref{eq:kernel_schwarzian} yields a causal, oscillatory-decaying $\Xi^R(u-u')$ with characteristic ``comb-like'' temporal features, directly feeding into the $g^{(2)}$ sidebands predicted by HMC. This explicit derivation from the JT/Schwarzian mode provides a concrete, microphysical origin for the memory kernel, its magnitude ($\sim 1/S_{\rm BH}$), and its characteristic timescales.

\paragraph{From Schwarzian to HMC postulates.}
- \emph{P0}: $C\propto S_{\rm BH}$ ties the Schwarzian Hilbert space size to area.
- \emph{P1}: The JT boundary/matter system evolves unitarily; the boundary mode acts as a persistent memory register.
- \emph{P2}: The Schwarzian dynamics exhibit maximal chaos with $\lambda_L=2\pi/\beta$.
- \emph{P3}: $\Xi^R\propto 1/C\sim 1/S_{\rm BH}$ implies gentleness.
- \emph{P4}: As $C$ decreases with the shrinking dilaton at the horizon, the influence of the memory mode shifts information into the radiation via the kernel-mediated entanglement swapping, implementing adiabatic transfer.

\section{Field-Theoretic Underpinning: An Influence Functional with Memory}
\label{sec:influence}

Integrating out horizon memory (edge/Schwarzian modes) yields an influence functional
\begin{align}
    \mathcal{F}[\phi_+, \phi_-]=\exp\Bigg\{ & i\int \!du\,du'\,\Big(\phi_+(u)-\phi_-(u)\Big)\,\Xi(u, u')\,\Big(\phi_+(u')+\phi_-(u')\Big) \nonumber \\
    & + \text{higher order terms} \Bigg\},
    \label{eq:influence_functional}
\end{align}
with $\Xi(u,u')$ causal and gentle. From the microscopic couplings (Eqs.~\eqref{eq:boundary_int}, \eqref{eq:JT_coupling}), the kernel is the retarded two-point function of the edge/Schwarzian operator. In frequency space, Eq.~\eqref{eq:kernel_schwarzian} gives an explicit, universal form in JT gravity with amplitude $\sim 1/S_{\rm BH}$.

\subsection{Modified Spectra and Correlations}
Bogoliubov coefficients acquire $O(\varepsilon)$ corrections, $\varepsilon\sim 1/S_{\rm BH}$:
\begin{equation}
    n_\omega \approx \frac{1}{e^{\omega/T_H}-1}\ \Big(1 + 2\,\varepsilon\,\Re[\mathcal{T}(\omega)]\Big),
\end{equation}
with $\mathcal{T}(\omega)$ the transform of $\Xi$. The two-time intensity correlation $g^{(2)}(\Delta u)$ is
\begin{equation}
    g^{(2)}(\Delta u)\ =\ 1+\varepsilon\,\mathcal{C}(\Delta u;\tau_{\rm mem})+O(\varepsilon^2),
\end{equation}
exhibiting ``comb sidebands'' decaying on $\tau_{\rm mem}$, consistent with a Schwarzian-derived kernel (Eq.~\eqref{eq:kernel_schwarzian}).

\section{Experimental Results and Ablations}
\label{sec:experiments}

\subsection{Non-Markovian Temporal Correlations: Comb Sidebands}
We generate an idealized, causal, oscillatory-decaying correlation model for $g^{(2)}$, $g^{(2)}(\Delta u)=1+\varepsilon \cos(\omega_{\rm mem}\Delta u)\, e^{-\Delta u/\tau_{\rm mem}}$, with bootstrapped 95\% CIs over multiple realizations. Figure~\ref{fig:g2} displays mean with CI bands.

