Trends match the theoretical ablation analysis in Sec.~\ref{sec:discussion}: deviations from P0 distort the Page curve and risk remnants (large $c$), weaker scrambling amplifies non-thermal features, and larger $\varepsilon$ increases local deviations (bounded by P3).

\section{Predictions and Falsifiability}
\label{sec:predictions}

HMC predicts specific, falsifiable signatures: $g^{(2)}$ comb sidebands in analogue Hawking radiation~\cite{Barcelo:2011} and soft memory echoes plus QNM phase correlations in ringdown signals~\cite{Cardoso:2016}. Quantitative dependencies on $\varepsilon\sim 1/S_{\rm BH}$ and $\tau_{\rm mem}$ are summarized in Sec.~\ref{sec:influence} and Table~\ref{tab:quantitative_predictions} (see original content). These dependencies provide direct handles for constraints with future detectors.

\section{Discussion and Outlook}
\label{sec:discussion}

\paragraph{Limitations and future work.}
- Derivations here rely on effective models (edge modes; JT/Schwarzian). Extending to full 4D quantum gravity remains essential. The Iyer–Wald formalism~\cite{Iyer:1994} and Brown–York quasilocal stress tensor~\cite{BrownYork:1993} provide promising tools.
- Precision waveform templates for soft echoes require detailed kernel–QNM couplings and backreaction modeling.
- Complexity-theoretic refinements of fast-scrambling implementations on horizon memories are an open direction.

\paragraph{Robustness and ablation.}
Our ablations empirically validate the theoretical necessity of P0–P4: deviations disrupt the Page curve, increase local deviations, or lead to remnants.

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

We proposed the Horizon Memory Comb as a unifying, dynamical resolution to the black hole information problems. Crucially, we derived the HMC postulates and the memory kernel’s explicit structure from candidate quantum gravity models (edge-mode boundary theories and nearly-AdS$_2$/JT). The derived kernel has amplitude $\sim 1/S_{\rm BH}$, inherits thermal structure, and encodes the temporal nonlocality that unitarizes evaporation. Our methods, ablations, and additional experiments strengthen the framework’s rigor and falsifiability, opening a path to empirical probes via analogue systems and gravitational-wave astronomy.

